The article is maybe overblown, but I think there&#x27;s a good point there. A lot of functionality is one-off stuff that doesn&#x27;t need to be re-used and won&#x27;t be, and so trying to come up with a name for a little chunk of code just ends up making the program harder to understand.<p>So, sure, you can write:<p><pre><code>  function processData(err, data) {
    //blah blah does stuff
  }

  db.getData(processData);
</code></pre>
But it&#x27;s actually a lot simpler and more understandable if you just write:<p><pre><code>  db.getData(function (err, data) { 
    //blah blah does stuff
  });
</code></pre>
If and when you ever need to break that function out into something re-usable, give it a name then, but don&#x27;t bother with a name unless you need it.
